<TEXT>
a us supreme court justice monday 
temporarily halted creation of a new governing board to oversee 
desegregation of louisianas 17 public colleges and universities 
the ruling by justice byron r white who acted on emergency 
requests from state attorney general william guste and the southern 
university board of supervisors came as a state senate committee 
began confirmation hearings on 17 nominees for the governing board 
john kennedy an attorney for gov buddy roemer who opposes the 
delay agreed with guste that the case raises major constitutional 
questions on desegregation of colleges and universities 
but in a brief filed with the high court kennedy said attempts 
to postpone creation of the new board are politically motivated and 
would hinder racial intergration keeping the southern board is 
merely another form of separatism which cannot be constitutionally 
condoned the brief said 
a threejudge federal panel in new orleans ordered the 
abolishment of the states four governing boards for higher 
education as part of a plan to desegregate louisianas higher 
education system under the panels ruling the board is scheduled 
to begin operations friday 
whites order stops the elimination of the southern board until 
the full supreme court receives a response by justice department 
lawyers the order did not impose a deadline for the response guste 
and the southern board want the desegregation plan stopped until the 
full supreme court can hear an appeal 
the case began in 1974 when the justice department sued on behalf 
of black students prompting the threejudge court to rule that 
the present scheme has perpetuated illegal segregation in 
louisianas higher education 
last year the court ruled that a 1981 consent decree had failed 
to desegregate colleges and universities the agreement had called 
for the state to spend millions of dollars to upgrade southern and 
grambling state university the states predominantly black 
universities 
guste and the southern board contend that the state is not 
responsible for any vestiges of segregation that remain in 
louisianas higher education system and the fourboard system set 
up by the state constitution should not be scuttled 
we have had over 20 years without any legally imposed 
segregation a whole generation of students has grown up they are 
exercising their constitutional right of freedom of choice of 
academic programs and constitutional right of freedom of 
association guste said during a news conference 
guste said the proposed single board has been given a strict 
timetable to implement a desegregation plan including creation of a 
community college system and specified roles and missions for each 
university most of the changes are required to be implemented 
within 120 days 
a full appeal to the supreme court would take about a year guste 
said 
can you imagine what would happen a year from now if the court 
went back to the four boards it would be total confusion he said 
</TEXT>
