<TEXT>
behind the lives destroyed in 20 years of violence 
in northern ireland lies another casualty the corruption of civil 
liberties in britain itself 
in its attempts to crush the irish republican army a nation 
that ranks among the worlds older democracies has adopted laws 
which opponents say would look more at home in a dictatorship 
prime minister margaret thatcher defends the practice of 
detaining suspects for a week without charging them or banning 
british radio and television stations from broadcasting interviews 
with ira members as part of the price for fighting terrorism 
to beat off your enemy in a war you have to suspend some of 
your civil liberties for a time she said after last octobers 
imposition of the broadcast ban which also covers members and 
sympathizers of 10 other militant groups 
none of us can be neutral as between the terrorist and the 
lawabiding citizen added mrs thatcher who survived an ira 
hotel bombing in 1984 that killed five people including two senior 
conservative party figures 
her critics however detect a gradual warping of democratic 
freedoms since the troubles flared and britain dispatched 
troops on aug 14 1969 to keep northern irelands protestants and 
catholics apart twenty years later the troops remain 
the financial times of london in an editorial in december 
commented on a lengthening list of recent government decisions 
each of which has given greater weight to reasons of state than to 
the civic rights of the individual most but not all arise from 
the troubles in northern ireland 
however the most controversial legislation the prevention of 
terrorism act is a legacy of a labor government enacted in 1978 
after 21 civilians were killed by an ira bomb in an english pub 
the act which applies throughout what is known formally as the 
united kingdom of great britain and northern ireland includes 
police powers to detain suspects for up to a week without charge 
in the decade of rule by mrs thatchers conservative 
government northern irelands death toll climbed past 2700 and 
britain has been cited 21 times the most by any country for 
violating the european convention on human rights 
her government imposed the broadcast ban on paramilitary groups 
and limited or proposed limiting the right of a suspect to remain 
silent 
since last fall courts in northern ireland have been able to 
interpret an accuseds silence after arrest as an indication in 
some circumstances of guilt those circumstances are 
failing to mention during interrogation any fact offered in 
defense at trial 
refusing to be sworn or answer questions at trial 
failing to explain any possessions or marks on the defendants 
clothing or person at the time of arrest 
failing to give an account for being at a particular place at 
the time of arrest 
the courts themselves which are convened without juries which 
might be intimidated or split along sectarian lines are also an 
extraordinary step taken in 1973 to combat terrorism 
last month a government advisory panel proposed limiting the 
right of silence for ordinary criminals in england and wales 
regulations under the antiterrorist act have been used to 
compel photographers and television stations to hand over material 
to help police investigations 
tv networks complained their crews were put in added danger 
after being compelled last year to hand over unscreened footage of 
an ira funeral march in which two british soldiers were murdered by 
a mob 
wed been pushed another step down a road with an uncertain 
ending commented roger bolton an executive with londons thames 
television station after giving police tape of an interview with a 
suspected terrorist 
britains runins with the european court of human rights are 
partly due to the fact that this country has no written bill of 
rights or constitution and thus issues are automatically 
transferred to the court in strasbourg france instead of being 
filtered through domestic courts 
last november britain refused to implement a ruling by the 
19judge court that the antiterrorism acts detention powers 
violate the european human rights convention and should be repealed 
the case was brought by four northern ireland men who were held 
for between 4 days and a week in 1984 and then released 
britain invoked an article of the convention that says the 
ruling need not be accepted in time of war or public emergency 
threatening the life of the nation 
</TEXT>
