<TEXT>
when solidarity agreed last spring to take 
only 35 percent of parliament seats union strategists saw it as 
the first step in a smooth fouryear transition from a oneparty 
state to full democracy 
but they did not reckon with the explosion in public 
expectations that followed solidaritys election victory in june 
or the sudden deterioration in the economy 
poles dont want to wait for change and thats the reason 
solidarity leader lech walesa gave when he made an aboutface last 
week and urged formation of a solidarityled coalition government 
according to senator jaroslaw kaczynski acting as walesas 
personal envoy in the coalition talks walesa himself might become 
prime minister 
it is a far cry from the plan articulated by solidarity 
strategists after last springs agreement that set the stage for 
the oppositions entrance into parliamentary politics 
as originally conceived solidarity would use this parliamentary 
term to monitor communist authorities from the opposition bench 
while getting familiar with the nuts and bolts of government and 
creating independent political parties to win elections in 1993 
in the meantime the communist party and polands east bloc 
allies especially the soviet union would have time to 
accommodate themselves to the notion of a noncommunist poland 
two months after the elections that timetable already is 
looking outdated 
desperately counting on changes for the better poles standing 
in line for such basics as bread and meat are in no mood to talk 
about waiting until 1993 for a change in government 
industrial production is falling food prices went up sharply 
aug 1 store shelves are often empty and there are signs poland is 
slipping into hyperinflation 
when the communist party named three familiar faces to the 
countrys three top jobs gen wojciech jaruzelski as president 
mieczyslaw f rakowski as party chief and gen czeslaw kiszczak as 
prime minister the publics patience seemed to snap 
walesas quest for the government is a reaction to the resulting 
social impatience said senator aleksander paszynski 
we asked ourselves can we wait the answer is no said 
solidaritys parliamentary leader bronislaw geremek 
as early as june 2 jaruzelski had proposed a grand 
coalition government whose distribution of ministries would 
reflect more or less the proportion of voting strength in 
parliament that is twothirds of the cabinet for the communist 
coalition and onethird for solidarity 
then walesa replied in essence no thanks well stay in 
opposition 
he did not want solidaritys name tarnished in the kind of phony 
coalition rule that took place in poland after world war ii then 
figurehead ministers of various political stripes served to 
camouflage the communist consolidation of power beneath the surface 
as a counterproposal just before kiszczaks election walesa 
offered to take on the whole government including the defense and 
police ministries 
jaruzelski as walesa could have expected rejected that 
according to opposition lawmakers jaruzelski made clear that the 
soviet union would not support a solidarity government 
but after kiszczaks election as prime minister aug 2 as the 
protests rose from grassroots solidarity chapters walesa went on 
the offensive 
he called for a noncommunist coalition government that would 
include solidarity and the previously communistallied minor 
parties the peasants and the democrats 
geremek broadened the offer proposing places in the government 
to reformist communists 
walesas move has touched off a flurry of meetings and 
consultations with the peasants and democrats expressing interest 
there have been rumblings of worry from moscow 
the soviet ambassador even went to talk to the leaders of the 
two minor parties 
where it will end is anyones guess all that can be said is 
that the options for the next government have been significantly 
widened 
by merely putting up a fight for the government walesa has 
scored at least three political successes 
he has put the communists on the defensive forcing them to 
justify to public opinion why they should lead the government 
he has widened the rifts within the communist coalition 
provoking the normally reliable democrats and peasants to show 
unprecedented independence 
and he has protected solidarity from charges that it was 
unwilling to take responsibility for leading the country 
now the stage is set for hard political bargaining 
jaruzelskis original idea of a grand coalition government 
that would include some combination of communists and solidarity 
ministers may still become a reality but under terms negotiated to 
walesas satisfaction 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
john daniszewski the warsaw correspondent of 
the associated press has covered polish affairs since 1987 
