<TEXT>
farmers who grow socalled minor crops may 
want to band together to help pesticide manufacturers supply data 
needed to keep chemicals on the market says a spokesman for the 
national agricultural chemicals association 
manufacturers will not make pesticides that are not 
profitable said ray s mcallister director of regulatory 
affairs for the naca 
many pesticides used on minor crops are being dropped because of 
the high cost of tests needed to prove to the environmental 
protection agency that any residue left on the food is harmless to 
humans he said 
i dont envision the individual farmer getting involved 
said mcallister but there may be a group producing a specialty 
crop that could supply the resources for doing the tests he said 
examples of crops affected are berries cucumbers melons 
squashes kale mustard greens rutabaga spinach turnips 
asparagus celery lettuce onion peppers pimiento peanuts 
sunflowers kumquats papaya sugar beets and garlic 
an naca survey directed by mcallister found that manufacturers 
plan to cancel 20 commonly used pesticides because of the testing 
requirements while 39 others would be canceled for at least one 
food use cost of testing was the most frequently cited reason for 
dropping a chemical 
the testing requirement is mandated by the 1988 amendments to 
the federal insecticide fungicide and rodenticide act 
this is the first time complete reregistration is being 
done said arthur grube economic analyst with the epa he said 
it is to be completed by 1997 
it is probable that some chemicals will disappear he said 
saying they would be the ones used in relatively small volumes 
which require significant testing 
but he said congress decided that if this stuff was going out 
into the environment it was worth it to know how safe it is 
he acknowledged that over the years laws have become more 
demanding because technology exists to research longterm health 
effects of chemical use instead of just the immediate result of 
exposure 
we are going to pay for it said grube but i think if you 
asked most people if they were willing to pay a dollar more for 
groceries to be assured the pesticide used on the food wouldnt 
cause cancer theyd pay it 
the epa has said it will try to be flexible with chemical 
manufacturers on some of the testing 
mcallister said for example if a chemical has already been 
tested on one kind of produce he has been told certain assumptions 
would be allowed without further tests on its effects on other 
foods 
meanwhile rep george brown dcalif will hold hearings next 
month on legislation that would speed up the removal of pesticides 
with proven health risks 
the bill would create a review process to continually upgrade 
health and safety information on pesticides and put an early 
warning system in place to keep agriculture research and 
extension work ahead of pesticide regulatory decisions he said 
it would change the cancellation process which currently 
requires administrative hearings and grants a transition period to 
farmers left with no pest control alternatives 
brown is chairman of the house agriculture subcommittee on 
department operations research and foreign agriculture 
