<TEXT>
the state of connecticut has settled a 
federal lawsuit by agreeing to stop segregating inmates suffering 
from aids 
this consent decree reflects our new knowledge and 
understanding of aids clarine nardi riddle acting connecticut 
attorney general said today 
judy greenspan of the american civil liberties unions national 
prison project in washington praised the settlement as a landmark 
attorneys said the settlement could affect similar lawsuits pending 
in california and alabama 
by not segregating those with fullblown aids connecticut will 
set an example for the rest of the country greenspan said 
william flower a spokesman for the state prison system said the 
state stopped housing aids patients separately about six months ago 
in response to the suit 
before that inmates with aids symptoms were confined to an aids 
ward for up to 23 hours a day at the maximumsecurity prison in 
somers they were not allowed to take part in education recreation 
and religious programs 
under the settlement there no longer will be a separate aids 
ward said deborah chang an attorney for the inmates 
inmates attorneys had charged that inmates put in the aids ward 
with serious aidsrelated symptoms were kept there even after 
showing improvement 
the result was that a lot of people in the prison population 
who were hivinfected refused to go for treatment said chang 
five aidsinfected inmates had brought the classaction lawsuit 
against the state in 1988 three of the inmates have since died 
flower said there is no reliable estimate of the number of 
inmates infected with the aids virus at last count five were being 
treated for aidsrelated illnesses in the systems acute care unit 
he said 
but there is no mandatory testing for the virus and some 
officials have estimated that as many as 25 percent of the prison 
systems 8800 inmates carry the virus 
</TEXT>
