<DOCNO> AP890814-0077 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
some 270000 american adults are suffering a 
serious stress reaction from the killing of a family member a new 
study estimates 
and about 1 million have suffered such a homiciderelated case of 
posttraumatic stress disorder at some point in their lives the 
study says 
it also estimated that 5 million americans older than 18 have 
lost an immediate family member to homicide and an additional 114 
million have lost other relatives or close friends 
the sudden violent death of a family member brings with it 
serious psychological consequences for many family survivors said 
angelynne amick a clinical psychologist and assistant professor at 
the medical university of south carolina 
she discussed the work sunday at the annual meeting of the 
american psychological association the study defined homicide as 
being killed by a criminal or a drunk driver 
posttraumatic stress disorder includes such symptoms as 
persistent and intrusive reliving of the trauma and a general 
numbing of responsiveness 
the study involved a national survey of about 12000 people and 
detailed interviews with a nationally representative sample of 214 
of them amick said 
two other studies of people affected by crimes against others 
focused on the impact of rape 
one work found that those emotionally close to a rape victim the 
people to whom she turns for support often share the social 
stereotypes of rape as at least in part the womans fault said 
researcher ellen brickman 
preliminary results from a study of 75 people close to victims of 
rape or assault found that rape victims were more often blamed for 
the incident than assault victims were she said 
when blame is communicated it does not seem to affect the amount 
of emotional or practical support from the people doing the blaming 
said brickman of the victim services agency in new york 
this complex mix of reactions must be studied further brickman 
said the reactions can have a profound impact on what the people 
closest to the victim communicate to her and how the victim 
endures the aftermath of violent crime she said 
another study suggests that nonsupportive behaviors of other 
people have a stronger impact on a rape victims recovery than 
supportive behaviors do 
nonsupportive behaviors include refusing to discuss the 
incident telling the victim to forget about it blaming her for it 
and asking the victim for emotional support for ones own problems 
said researcher robert davis 
supportive behaviors include such things as practical help with 
daily activities said davis of the new york victim services agency 
</TEXT>
