<TEXT>
business inventories rose 04 percent in june 
as business sales fell 03 percent the government said monday 
analysts said the report was in line with the economic 
softlanding sought by the federal reserve board slow but 
continued growth with low inflation 
inventories often rise during periods of slow economic growth as 
production exceeds demand a process that sometimes leads to a loss 
of jobs as businesses cut their output 
economists however said recent inventorytosales ratios are 
not unusually high 
inventories are not out of hand yet said howard roth of 
security pacific national bank in los angeles 
the basic message is that inventory vulnerability is fairly 
limited in the economy commented robert g dederick chief 
economist for the northern trust co of chicago this suggests 
that the prospect of an outright recession is limited 
inventories held on shelves and backlots climbed to a seasonally 
adjusted 7808 billion in june the commerce department said the 
04 percent jump followed increases of 09 percent in may and 08 
percent in april 
business sales meanwhile fell 03 percent to a seasonally 
adjusted 5164 billion after rising 01 percent in may and 2 
percent in april the department said sales had last fallen in 
february when they were down 09 percent 
the june report was consistent with recent indicators that 
economic growth had slowed as the federal reserve tightened credit 
to restrain inflation 
in a report friday the labor department said wholesale prices 
one step short of retail had fallen 04 percent in july their 
biggest decline in three years at the same time the commerce 
department reported that retail sales in july had risen a strong 09 
percent after falling 01 percent in june 
roth said the july retail sales report means well probably 
have pretty strong business sales in next report as far as the 
economy is concerned it looks like the softlanding scenario is 
still pretty good 
mondays business sales report includes transactions at three 
levels manufacturing wholesale and retail 
the ratio of inventories to sales in june was 151 meaning it 
would take 151 months to exhaust inventories at the june sales 
pace the ratio had stood at 150 in may and 149 in april 
manufacturers inventories which represent 47 percent of the 
total rose 03 percent while retailers stocks were up 06 
percent wholesalers registered a 01 percent increase 
total inventories were 82 percent higher than in june 1988 
manufacturers sales on the other hand fell 05 percent 
wholesalers sales were off 03 percent while retailers sales were 
down 01 percent 
overall sales were up 62 percent from a year ago 
</TEXT>
