<TEXT>
here are provisions of the farm disaster relief 
bill signed by president bush 
the new law 
authorizes an estimated 897 million in federal payments for 
farmers suffering crop losses from 35 percent to 50 percent this 
year because of weatherrelated disasters ranging from drought to 
flooding assistance also would go for replanting fruit trees killed 
by freeze and to small commercial growers who lose trees from 
drought and wildfires this year 
provides payments covering 65 percent of a farmers projected 
lost income from the crop damage in most instances the income 
levels will be based on federal crop subsidies or average market 
prices farmers would have received had they not suffered losses 
expands existing emergency livestock feed and water programs to 
provide more assistance for producers facing droughtrelated 
shortages for their herds for example the law will make money 
available to farmers to provide water for livestock raised in 
confinement facilities and to build or deepen ponds used to water 
livestock 
caps benefits at 100000 for each producer and prohibits 
payments to those with 2 million or more in gross farm revenues 
requires farmers who received disaster assistance to buy federal 
crop insurance in 1990 if their losses this year exceeded 65 percent 
here are the different eligibility standards under the new law 
producers of wheat corn cotton rice and other feed grains 
participating in federal commodity programs and who purchased 
federal crop insurance would be eligible for assistance on losses 
above 35 percent 
farmers without crop insurance but growing the socalled 
program crops must suffer losses of at least 40 percent tobacco 
peanuts and sugar beets are treated as program crops 
soybean and sunflower farmers would be eligible for assistance 
if they suffered losses above 45 percent regardless of whether they 
purchased crop insurance 
most crops not covered by government commodity programs 
everything from cherries and peaches to dry edible beans and 
potatoes must suffer losses exceeding 50 percent 
the same 50 percent loss requirement would apply to farmers who 
are not enrolled in federal commodity programs but grow wheat corn 
grain sorghum and other socalled program crops 
the agriculture department said it soon will publish regulations 
to carry out the program and inform state and county offices of the 
agricultural stabilization and conservation service of how it works 
the law requires the program to be phased in over the next 45 
days spokesman ray waggoner noted 
he said livestock producers winter wheat farmers and others 
should be able to figure losses quickly from crops already 
harvested while more time will be needed to tally the losses from 
corn soybeans and other crops being harvested in the fall 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
