<TEXT>
scientists at europes new particle accelerator 
the worlds biggest said monday they have produced the first 
specimens of a kind of particle from which they expect to gain clues 
to the basic forces of nature 
the successful start of the atom smasher the large 
electronpositron collider paves the way for ensuring europes 
position at the forefront of particle physics research throughout 
the next decade the european laboratory for particle physics said 
in a statement 
scientists shooting beams of particles electrons and positrons 
around the 17mile circular tunnel under the swissfrench border 
reporded the lep produced its first socalled z particle sunday 
said the lab known by its former french acronym cern 
a month after its first test run leps giant detectors more 
than 5000 magnets and other parts have proven to be working and 
ready to produce results cern said 
by the fall lep is expected to produce thousands of zs daily 
creating a greater scope for detailed study than its innovative but 
less prolific us competitor the stanford linear accelerator at 
menlo park calif according to the statement 
lep built over eight years with 13 billion swiss francs 790 
million from cerns 14 members states is the most powerful 
particle accelerator and the largest scientific instrument ever 
made according to cern 
it said the machine will recreate with new sophistication the 
dense swirl of matter just after the big bang the explosion 
scientists believe created the universe 15 billion years ago 
z particles existed naturally only for an instant after the big 
bang by watching them decay into other particles cern scientists 
hope to get new insight into the structure of matter and the 
development of the universe 
in particular results of the z experiments are expected to help 
complete a scientific model explaining the interaction of natures 
postulated four basic forces gravity electromagnetism and the 
weak and strong forces 
carlo rubbia the italian physics professor who heads cern 
shared the 1984 physics nobel prize with dutch scientist simon van 
der meer for discovering the z at cern but stronger colliders were 
needed to make enough so scientists can draw wellfounded 
conclusions from the random ways the particle breaks down 
one of the most fascinating results may be the discovery of an as 
yet theoretical particle believed to be the key to mass why things 
weight what they do 
