quintets for oboe and strings by arnold bax and arthur bliss 
phantasy quartet for oboe violin viola and cello op 2 by 
benjamin britten pamela woods oboe and the audubon quartet telarc 
 
telarc dipped into the cleveland orchestra for pamela woods 
assistant principal there and a journeywoman oboist who has played 
with the cincinnati san antonio and baltimore orcehstras for this 
satisfying program of english oboe music 
add her fat tone seamless lines and fine musicianship to the 
superlative audubon and the result is an excellent disc woods 
rich round sound unburdened by a heavy vibrato blends perfectly 
with the quartet all are equals if any fault can be found it is 
that ms woods is sometimes on the nonchalant side when the music 
needs a little more heat 
the program is coherent the pieces were composed between 1922 
and 1932 all inspired by the great english oboist leon goossens 
the baxblissbritten order moves from less tonal complexity to 
more the pieces most in the bax and least in the britten have 
elements of british folk tunes and all revel in a richness of 
texture 
bax also a poet who published under the name dermot obyrne was 
enamored of ireland and travelled widely there the quintets folk 
melodies most apparent in the last movement bear out that bit of 
biography the piece has a lush quality and reminds one of the ravel 
string quartet doris lederers viola solos are particularly 
beautiful 
bliss a world war i veteran succeeded bax as master of the 
queens music and his quintet sounds inspired by the bax work his 
variety of colors is greater and brittens even greater still 
britten was 18 when he finished his phantasy it is one of his 
earliest mature works 
by daniel wakin associated press writer 
