<TEXT>
a 3weekold strike at american assembly 
plants along the border is threatening the growth of the industry 
nationwide plant officials said monday theyre asking the 
president of mexico to end it 
the 15 strikeclosed plants in the border city of reynosa want 
the citys other 27 assembly operations to cease production in 
sympathy said don king manager of reynosas west bend plant one 
of the affected companies 
some of the plants in reynosa have been closed for three weeks 
and to date we have not received any indication of support from the 
tamaulipas state government except promises the companies said 
in a letter addressed to president carlos salinas de gortari 
salinas was out of town monday and did not respond immediately to 
the request 
we are with you in your modernization program and your fight 
against corruption but we need your action as soon as possible 
the letter said 
the foreignoperated assembly plants most of them 
americanowned have been closed since july 25 over a power struggle 
between two union leaders 
union leader rafael morales put up red and black strike flags on 
the gates of plants whose laborers had organized under leader abel 
hernandez 
morales argued that hernandez had failed among other things to 
get union control over the transportation of raw and finished 
materials and the disposal of scrap 
morales also argues that hernandez can no longer represent the 
workers because hernandez withdrew recently from the federation of 
mexican laborers or ctm said king 
king said however under mexican labor law we dont have to 
have a union affiliated with the ctm 
he said the companies contend that strike is illegal because only 
workers not a rival union have the right to strike against a 
company 
king said labor law prohibits workers from crossing a strike 
banner and american companies would not urge their employees to do 
so 
it concerns the safety of our workers he said 
king said the strikeclosed plants are asking the rest of 
reynosas 42 maquiladoras to lock out workers as a demonstration 
of their support and a confirmation that they dont condone illegal 
activies by the union 
closing would put pressure on the mexican government to solve the 
problem since the plants provide foreign capital and jobs and the 
government does not want investors to get nervous 
although the state labor arbitration board already has ruled in 
favor of morales some of the companies say they will close down 
permanently unless higher authorities recognize hernandez king said 
tamaulipas state has had a history of labor instability he 
said 
the plants known as maquiladoras take advantage of cheap 
mexican labor to assemble products in mexico for export 
the government has made efforts in the 1980s to woo plants to 
this country because of jobs they provide and the badly needed 
foreign capital they bring in 
the industry has grown from 800 plants and 218000 employees in 
1985 to about 1400 plants and 392000 workers today 
the strike the industrys most severe in memory could affect 
the growth of the maquiladora industry in general depending on how 
this is resolved said king 
if the government is not going to support a foreign investor 
hes going to be more cautious about making an investment in this 
country he said 
but james gaffney vice president of the reynosa association of 
maquiladoras said monday that the plants have no response at this 
time to the request 
asked if his calzado de mexico plant which makes converse tennis 
shoes would support the strike gaffney said i havent talked to 
our corporate people yet 
about 27000 people work in the citys assembly plants the 
strike so far has locked about 2000 people out of their jobs 
the dispute has been in a federal court since last week but no 
decision has been made king said 
officials of invacare corp of elyria ohio said their invamex 
operations in reynosa were not operating monday but that they 
expected the labor problems to be ironed out soon 
the company which makes wheelchairs invested about 5 million 
to start up the plant last year and was planning to expand next year 
