<TEXT>
president bush on monday selected white house 
aide richard c breeden an attorney and banking specialist to be 
chairman of the securities and exchange commission 
breeden 39 has served in a variety of capacities under bush 
most recently as white house point man on the savingsandloan 
restructuring legislation 
the sec post requires senate confirmation 
breeden would succeed david s ruder who has headed the 
regulatory body since two months before the october 1987 stock 
market crash ruder announced in may that he was stepping down to 
accept a position at northwestern law school 
bush announced he technically would nominate breeden to be the 
numerical replacement for sec member charles c cox whose fouryear 
term had expired however the white house said in a statement that 
upon senate confirmation of breeden as coxs replacement bush would 
immediately designate breeden the new chairman 
ruder has indicated he will resign his regular sec seat once 
breeden was confirmed so bush then would have to fill that vacancy 
too 
according to the white house announcement breedens experience 
covers a wide range of securities banking and other financial 
transactions and matters both in the united states and 
internationally 
he is a 1972 graduate of stanford university and a 1975 graduate 
of the harvard law school from 1981 to 1982 breeden was an 
executive assistant to the under secretary of labor 
in advance of the formal announcement white house press 
secretary marlin fitzwater called breeden an outstanding 
candidate 
breeden helped draft the administrations initial plan for 
bailing out the nations ailing savings and loan industry submitted 
in february he also represented the white house in dealings with 
congress as that legislation progressed 
the final plan a sweeping rewriting of banking laws and the 
largest singleindustry government bailout ever was signed into law 
by bush last week at a rose garden ceremony attended by breeden 
breeden whose current job as presidential assistant for issues 
analysis made him something of a white house troubleshooter also 
helped fashion administration policy for dealing with the alaska oil 
spill 
from 1982 to 1985 breeden was deputy counsel to thenvice 
president bush 
he was a banking specialist with a new york law firm before that 
and between government assignments worked in the washington office 
of a houston law firm 
he was also the director of a task force on deregulation headed 
by bush as vice president and wrote the panels report on the 
deregulation of financial services 
the sec is a fivemember board that oversees securities markets 
regulates the sale of stocks bonds and stock options and enforces 
securities laws 
ruder an appointee of former president reagan has been chairman 
since aug 7 1987 
he announced last may that he wanted to return to northwestern 
where he once taught but would stay on until a successor was 
selected 
breedens nomination was not expected to run into any 
difficulties in the senate 
