<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency on monday 
said it plans to lower sulfur concentrations in diesel fuel to curb 
motor vehicle exhaust pollution and improve air quality in urban 
areas 
under the epa proposal which still must be adopted as a formal 
agency regulation refiners would be required to reduce the maximum 
permitted sulfur content of diesel fuel by 80 percent before october 
1993 
diesel engines are one of the major sources of particulate 
pollution or smoke and soot from motor vehicles in urban areas 
especially in major cities in the west sulfur compounds contribute 
to the problem forming fine acidic mists that can worsen breathing 
problems and contribute to acid rain 
heavyduty diesel engines are a major source of particulate 
emissions including the smaller fine particles that are of 
greatest concern in protecting public health said epa 
administrator william k reilly in a statement announcing the 
proposal 
the epa proposal would call for the same reduction in sulfur 
content in diesel fuel by 1993 from 025 percent by weight to 005 
percent as recently called for by state officials in california 
the california requirement also calls for changes in the fuel to 
reduce the level of certain pollutionpromoting chemicals called 
aromatic compounds epas proposal would cap concentrations at the 
current level instead of reducing them 
bob yuhnke an attorney for the environmental defense fund in 
denver said the epa is taking the right step in calling for 
reductions in sulfur but he criticized the agency for not also 
proposing reductions in the aromatic chemicals 
going only half way leaves the states holding the bag yuhnke 
said without additional curbs on diesel fuel emissions some states 
may have trouble meeting urban air quality requirements expected in 
clean air legislation now being debated in congress he said 
</TEXT>
